{
    "node_id": "time-matrix-11",
    "title": "Life Experience: Have You Ever?",
    "description": "Talking about things you have done in your life without a specific time.",
    "display_order": 11,
    "prerequisites": ["time-matrix-10"],
    "lesson_content_markdown": "# Life Experience: Have You Ever?\n\nSometimes, it is not important **when** you did something. What counts is that you **have** done it at some point in your life. We use the **Present Perfect** for this.\n\n### 1. How to Make It\nUse **have** or **has** + the **Past Participle** (V3).\n\n- **Formula**: Subject + have/has + V3 (e.g., eaten, been, visited)\n- **Example**: I **have visited** the university library many times.\n- **Example**: She **has studied** English for a long time.\n\n### 2. Common Regular V3 Forms (-ed)\nMost past participles are the same as the simple past form.\n- visit \u2192 **visited**\n- study \u2192 **studied**\n- finish \u2192 **finished**\n\n### 3. Common Irregular V3 Forms\n- go \u2192 **gone / been** (Use \"been\" if you went and came back!)\n- eat \u2192 **eaten**\n- write \u2192 **written**\n- see \u2192 **seen**\n- do \u2192 **done**\n\n### 4. Have you ever...?\nWe use **ever** in questions to mean \"at any time in your life.\"\n- **Example**: **Have you ever** lost your student ID card?\n- **Example**: **Has she ever** eaten at the campus cafe?\n\n---",
